This project demonstrates how Wireshark can be used to capture and inspect HTTP network traffic. Analyzing HTTP packets helps in understanding how web communication works between a client and a server. It also helps security analysts detect unusual activity, troubleshoot network problems, and study how web requests and responses are exchanged.

# Requirements

Before starting this lab, make sure you have the following:

Basic knowledge of networking and packet communication

Wireshark installed on your system

A web browser to generate HTTP traffic during the capture process

# Tools Used

Wireshark
Install Wireshark from the official website:
https://www.wireshark.org/download.html

Web Browser
Any browser such as Google Chrome, Mozilla Firefox, or Microsoft Edge can be used to generate web traffic.

#Practical Exercises

# Exercise 1: Capturing HTTP Packets
Steps

Launch the Wireshark application.

Choose the network interface that is currently connected to the internet.

Start packet capture by clicking the Start Capture icon.

Open a web browser and visit a website that uses HTTP (for example: http://example.com
).

Wait for the page to load fully and then stop the capture in Wireshark.

Result

The capture will contain multiple packets including HTTP requests and responses generated by the browser.

# Exercise 2: Display Only HTTP Traffic
Steps

Locate the display filter bar in Wireshark.

Type the following filter:

http

Press Enter to apply the filter.

Result

Wireshark will now show only HTTP-related packets from the captured traffic.

# Exercise 3: Inspect HTTP Requests
Steps

From the filtered packets, find an HTTP GET request.

Select the packet to view detailed information in the packet details panel.

Expand the Hypertext Transfer Protocol section to observe fields such as the requested URL, request headers, and additional parameters.

Result

You will be able to view the structure and details of an HTTP request sent by the browser.

# Exercise 4: Inspect HTTP Responses
Steps

Identify the HTTP response packet that corresponds to the GET request.

Click on that packet to open its details.

Expand the Hypertext Transfer Protocol section to see information such as response status code, server headers, and content type.

Result

The packet details will display how the server responded to the browser request.

Exercise 5: Viewing HTTP Payload Data
Steps

Look for payload content within the HTTP response packet.

Right-click the packet and select Follow → TCP Stream.

A new window will display the full conversation between the client and the server.

Result

The TCP stream view will show the actual data transferred, such as HTML content or other web resources.
